@node "commodity" "It's a commodity"
ETrashCan can be controlled from the commodities exchange. It can be removed,
or the appicon can be removed from and replaced on workbench with the
active/inactive cycle gadget.
@endnode

@node "volume_cycle_gadget" "Selecting a volume"
This gadget selects which volume you want to see the trashcan contents of.
Each disk keeps track of it's deleted files seperately. Select the disk you're
interested in here.
@endnode

@node "contents_lv" "Stuff that's in the can on this volume"
This list shows you what's in the trashcan on your current volume. To undelete
something, click on it. You will get a file requester. Use it to select the
directory where you want to put the undeleted file. You can only undelete a
file onto it's own volume.
@endnode

@node "check_box" "Keeping .info files with their owners "
If this box is checked then a file and it's associated .info file will be
undeleted together. eg if you undelete 'foo.info', then you will actually
undelete 'foo' as well. The state of this gadget is determined on startup by
the @{"UNDELETE_INFO" link "config" 0} tooltype.
@endnode

@node "EmptyTrash" "Empty All Trash"
When this button is selected the GUI will close. All files in @{b}all@{ub} the volumes
currently mounted will be deleted. When this has finished the appicon will
change to show the trashcans are empty (Assuming both full and empty icons
have been @{"configured" link "config" 0})
@endnode

@node "cancel" "Cancel"
This closes the GUI. Nothing further will happen.
@endnode

@node "gui_menus" "menus"
There are 3 menu items:

@{b}About@{ub} (R-Amiga A)
    Gives some information about the program and it's author

@{b}Hide@{ub} (R-Amiga H)
    Closes the GUI

@{b}Quit@{ub} (R-Amiga Q)
    Quits ETrashCan
@endnode

